Download R and R Studio

R is a language used heavily in statistical computing, totally free and open source, and popular in many scientific disciplines. RStudio is an integrated development environment that makes working with R more convenient.

Download the latest versions of R and RStudio.

R Projects

R projects are a convenient way to organize RStudio settings and working directories. You can just open your Rproject file and, assuming that the .Rproj file extension is associated with RStudio, RStudio will open and R will be working in the root directory of your project folder (in this case itâll be the folder where youâve put your github repo)

  1. Open R Studio
  2. Create a new RProject by clicking the top left R cube, dropping down a menu where you can select âNew Project.â

Then browse for the GitHub repo location you created when you cloned the remote repository.

The upper right corner of RStudio should now show the project name, which it takes from the folder name, and also a new âgitâ tab (that we wonât primarily use, but you can if you want):

Commit and push your folder to the remote location (Github)

  1. Go back to GitHub Desktop. You should now see your RProject has shown up as a changed file (git will track new files and changes in existing files).
  2. Commit your changes. Add a commit message that describes what the file changes are (again, in this case, itâs a new file). Then click âCommit 1 file to main.â This commits the changes in your local repository, but only sets up a change to your remote repository.

  1. Push your commit. To actually change the files on your remote location, you need to push them. When you have committed changes in your local repo, GitHub Desktop shows that those commits are ready to be pushed to the remote.

Now there should not be any option to either commit OR push changes from your local repository.

  1. Confirm the push worked.

You can double check that your push worked by looking directly at your remote Github repo. Go back to the URL and you should now see your RProject, with the commit message and the timing. Git and github keep track of these changes and their timing, creating a record where you can revert to different versions of your files/software. Thereâs a lot more power to git, but most of what we will be doing in this course is this commit/push cycle.
